  "companies": [],
  "statement": "# Combination Sum\n\nReturn all unique combinations where candidate numbers sum to `target`. A candidate may be reused any number of times.\n\n## Examples\n\n**Example 1**\n\n```text\nInput: candidates = [2,3,6,7], target = 7\nOutput: [[2,2,3],[7]]\n```\n\n**Example 2**\n\n```text\nInput: candidates = [3,4,5], target = 8\nOutput: [[3,5],[4,4]]\n```\n\n**Example 3**\n\n```text\nInput: candidates = [5], target = 3\nOutput: []\n```\n\n## Constraints\n\n- Candidate values are positive and unique.\n- Combination order is ignored.",
  "editorial": "Sort candidates and backtrack from a start index. Reusing the same index allows unlimited copies while preserving canonical combination order.",
  "solution_notes": "```python\nclass Solution:\n    def combinationSum(self, candidates, target):\n        candidates.sort()\n        out = []\n        def dfs(start, remain, path):\n            if remain == 0:\n                out.append(path[:])\n                return\n            for i in range(start, len(candidates)):\n                value = candidates[i]\n                if value > remain:\n                    break\n                path.append(value)\n                dfs(i, remain - value, path)\n                path.pop()\n        dfs(0, target, [])\n        return out\n```",
  "hints": [
    "Sorting lets you stop when a candidate is too large.",
    "Keep the same index when the candidate can be reused."
  ],
  "starter_code": {
    "python": "class Solution:\n    def combinationSum(self, candidates, target):\n        pass\n"
  },
